I have never, while I was a member of the government, attempted to bring a matter like this before parliament and do it in three or four words. .

Sir WILFRID LAURIER. My hon. friend is altogether too hasty in his conclusions. I am sorry to say that my portfolio has not come in containing my papers, as other- wise I would have been prepared to show the number of votes cast in each constitu- enc’y at the last election, and how many were cast in the proposed constituencies. In the meantime I will endeavour to give some information to the committee. The hon. gentleman has asked me what are the con- stituencies which are to remain as they have been. Well, ﬁrst of all the constitu- ency of Medicine Hat is about the same as it was before. Medicine Hat was in the dis- trict of Saskatchewan, now the greater portion of it is in the district of Alberta. It is larger by a few miles. The constituency Cardston is j'ust the same as it has been. Lethbridge is exactly the same as it was before. Macleod is divided into two, as it was one of the largest districts in the North- west Territories. So we have now the con- stituencies of Macleod and Pincher. High River is the same as it was before, exactly the same. Band? is a little larger than it was. Calgary, the limits are now conﬁned to the city, whereas before it comprised a portion of the country district. Then on the west of Calgary is Rosebud. The bound- aries of Gleichen are not the same.

Sir WILFRID LAURIER. I think a new one is made out Of West Calgary, by the name of Innisfail. Out of 'these two con— stituencies of East and West Calgary we have made three, Rosebud, Gleichen and the city of Calgary. I have explained to my hon. friend that Banﬁ is a little extended. A part of West and East Calgary has been added to Banff so as to equalize the popula- tion. Innisfail remains almost the same. There is a small change which is made in Innisfail, a small portion of the constituency being added to Red Deer.
